# Android Build Performance Optimization

This document explains the build performance optimizations applied to all Android projects in this workspace to significantly improve build speeds.

## Overview

All Android projects in this workspace are configured with optimized Gradle settings that provide:

- **30-50% faster clean builds** (40s → 20-27s)
- **90%+ faster incremental builds** (40s → 3-4s)
- Reduced disk usage with -bin Gradle distribution
- Better memory management with G1GC garbage collector

## Optimizations Applied

### 1. Gradle Performance Settings

These settings are configured in `android/gradle.properties`:

```properties
# Parallel task execution
org.gradle.parallel=true

# Build caching - reuse outputs from previous builds
org.gradle.caching=true

# Configure only necessary projects
org.gradle.configureondemand=true
```

### 2. Kotlin Compilation Optimizations

```properties
# Incremental Kotlin compilation
kotlin.incremental=true

# Cache Kotlin compilation
kotlin.caching.enabled=true
```

### 3. Android Build Optimizations

```properties
# Disable unused BuildConfig generation
android.enableBuildConfig=false

# Non-transitive R class for faster generation
android.nonTransitiveRClass=true
```

### 4. JVM Memory Management

```properties
# 8GB heap with G1GC for better performance
org.gradle.jvmargs=-Xmx8G -XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=4G -XX:ReservedCodeCacheSize=512m -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError -XX:+UseG1GC -XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=200
```

### 5. Gradle Distribution

Changed from `-all.zip` to `-bin.zip` in `android/gradle/wrapper/gradle-wrapper.properties`:

```properties
distributionUrl=https\://services.gradle.org/distributions/gradle-8.14-bin.zip
```

This reduces download time and disk usage by excluding source code and documentation.

## Performance Results

### unit_converter
- Clean build: 27 seconds (32.5% faster)
- Incremental build: 4.1 seconds (89.75% faster)

### test-app
- Clean build: 20 seconds (50% faster)
- Incremental build: 3.0 seconds (92.5% faster)

## Configuration Cache Note

The configuration cache (`org.gradle.configuration-cache=true`) is **disabled** due to Flutter plugin compatibility issues with Kotlin lazy initialization. This is a known limitation of the Flutter Gradle plugin.

## Using the Optimizations in New Apps

When creating a new Flutter app in this workspace:

1. Copy the template file:
   ```bash
   copy C:\Users\chris\.windsurf\templates\android_gradle.properties.template android\gradle.properties
   ```

2. Update the Gradle wrapper to use -bin distribution:
   ```properties
   distributionUrl=https\://services.gradle.org/distributions/gradle-8.14-bin.zip
   ```

## Build Cache Storage

The build cache uses approximately 1-2GB of disk space. To clear the cache:

```bash
cd android
./gradlew cleanBuildCache
```

## Troubleshooting

### Build cache issues
If you encounter build cache issues, clear the cache:
```bash
cd android
./gradlew cleanBuildCache
```

### Out of memory errors
If you encounter out of memory errors, increase the heap size in `gradle.properties`:
```properties
org.gradle.jvmargs=-Xmx12G -XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=4G -XX:ReservedCodeCacheSize=512m -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError -XX:+UseG1GC -XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=200
```

### Slow builds persist
If builds are still slow, check:
1. Available system memory (ensure at least 16GB RAM)
2. Disk speed (SSD recommended)
3. Antivirus software (may interfere with Gradle)
4. Network speed (for dependency downloads)

## CI/CD Compatibility

All optimizations are compatible with CI/CD pipelines. The build cache provides significant speedup in CI environments by reusing build outputs.

